C(etype, Treatment(reference='semantic'))[T.perceptual]    2.0050    0.2956     6.783    0.0000     7.426     4.161    13.255
                Days    0.2780    0.0525     5.299    0.0000     1.320     1.191     1.463
Days:C(etype, Treatment(reference='semantic'))[T.perceptual]   -0.1757    0.0621    -2.828    0.0047     0.839     0.743     0.947

======================================================================
SECTION 4: SUMMARY COMPARISON
======================================================================

--- log(Days) models (proportional change) ---
  Perceptual: b = 0.0819, p = 0.1129
  Semantic:   b = 0.6541, p = 0.0002
  Semantic slope is 8.0× larger (on log scale)

--- Linear Days models (absolute change per day) ---
  Perceptual: b = 0.1036, p = 0.0025
  Semantic:   b = 0.2784, p = 0.0000
  Perceptual slope is 0.4× larger (on linear scale)

--- Interpretation ---
The choice of time scale matters enormously here:
  - log(Days): semantic wins because 0.2%→3.7% is a larger RATIO
  - linear Days: perceptual should win because 6.2%→9.7% is a larger ABSOLUTE change
Both are 'correct' — they answer different questions:
  - log: 'Which error type is ACCELERATING fastest?'
  - linear: 'Which error type ADDS MORE errors per day?'
For Jason's question ('what drives the steeper recognition decline'),
the linear scale is more directly relevant — it tells you which
error type contributes more additional errors over time.

